## Overview  
**Sir David Adjaye OBE** (born September 22, 1966) is a Ghanaian-British architect renowned for his innovative designs that blend cultural heritage with modern aesthetics. He is best known for his work on the **Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture (NMAAHC)** in Washington, D.C., and has established himself as one of the most influential architects of his generation.

---

## Key Details  

- **Full Name:** Sir David Frank Adjaye OBE  
- **Born:** September 22, 1966, in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania  
- **Nationality:** Ghanaian-British  
- **Education:**  
  - London South Bank University (B.A. Architecture)  
  - Royal College of Art (Master’s in Architecture)  
- **Notable Works:**  
  - Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture (NMAAHC), Washington, D.C.  
  - 1199 SEIU United Healthcare Workers East Building, New York  
  - National Cathedral of Ghana, Accra  
  - Museum of Contemporary Art Denver  

---

## Timeline  

- **1966 (20th Century):** Born in Tanzania to Ghanaian parents.  
- **1994 (20th Century):** Completed his architectural studies at the Royal College of Art.  
- **2000 (21st Century):** Founded his architecture firm, **Adjaye Associates**, in London.  
- **2009 (21st Century):** Designed the Moscow School of Management, establishing his global reputation.  
- **2016 (21st Century):** Completed the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.  
- **2017 (21st Century):** Knighted by Queen Elizabeth II for his services to architecture.  

